riscv: provide RV32 integer multiply/divide libcalls (no M extension)

Companion to patch 0001 (rv32i -march). With the M extension fully
removed from the build target -- hardware MUL / MULH[SU|U] AND
DIV / DIVU / REM / REMU all gone -- GCC lowers every C integer
multiply, division and modulo to a libcall:

  32-bit *           -> __mulsi3
  64-bit *           -> __muldi3
  32-bit / %         -> __divsi3 / __udivsi3 / __modsi3 / __umodsi3
  64-bit / %         -> __divdi3 / __udivdi3 / __moddi3 / __umoddi3
                        (and the combined __udivmoddi4)
  overflow-checked * -> __mulodi4   (-fsanitize / __builtin_*_overflow)

The kernel does not link libgcc, and arch/riscv/lib/ historically ships
no integer mul/div helpers at all -- the RV32 kernel relied entirely on
hardware M. So we add two files:

  arch/riscv/lib/mul32.c -- __mulsi3 / __muldi3 / __mulodi4
  arch/riscv/lib/div32.c -- the __[u]divsi3 / __[u]modsi3 family plus
                            the 64-bit __[u]divdi3 / __[u]moddi3 /
                            __udivmoddi4 family

CRITICAL CONSTRAINT: every routine here is compiled for -march=rv32i
too, so it must NOT itself contain a mul / div / rem opcode -- those
would trap. Therefore:

  * multiply is a shift+add ("Russian-peasant") loop -- shifts, adds
    and compares only;
  * division is a restoring shift-subtract long-division loop -- shifts,
    subtracts and compares only;
  * 64-bit multiply is built from 32-bit shift+add (no widening mul);
  * 64-bit divide is a 64-bit restoring shift-subtract loop.

None of them references `*`, `/` or `%` on integers, so GCC has nothing
to lower into an M opcode or a recursive libcall. (Pointer arithmetic
and constant power-of-two shifts the compiler folds to shifts are fine.)

All routines are EXPORT_SYMBOL'd so loadable modules built for the same
target resolve them too. This mirrors how arches without hardware
multiply/divide (m68k nommu, some arm variants, ...) carry their own
__mulsi3 / __divsi3 family in arch/*/lib/.

64-bit shift libcalls (__ashldi3 / __ashrdi3 / __lshrdi3) are NOT
provided here: GCC always inlines 64-bit shifts on rv32 (they need only
the base-I shift instructions), so they never become libcalls. If a
future toolchain change made them libcalls, the link would fail loudly
with an undefined-reference -- an obvious, non-silent signal -- and a
sibling file could be added then.

